 <title class="title" xmlns="">Author Biographies</title>
 <p class="p" xmlns="">
  <bold class="bold">J. Gordon Arbuckle Jr.</bold> is an associate professor of sociology at the Iowa State University. His research and extension activities center on improving the social and environmental performance of agriculture, with a particular focus on adaptation of agriculture to climate change, water quality, and agri-environmental policy and practice in general.
 </p>
 <p class="p" xmlns="">
  <bold class="bold">Lois Wright Morton</bold> is a professor of sociology at the Iowa State University and project director for the Climate and Corn-Based Cropping Systems Coordinated Agricultural Project (CAP). Her research centers on agriculture and natural resource management, specifically water quality, farmer conservation decision making, performance-based environmental management, grassland biodiversity management on working agricultural lands, and farmer response and adaptation to long-term changes in weather patterns.
 </p>
 <p class="p" xmlns="">
  <bold class="bold">Jon Hobbs</bold> is a doctoral student in statistics and meteorology at the Iowa State University. His research focuses on the development of spatioâ€“temporal statistical models to illustrate various aspects of the climate system, using observational and computer model data.
 </p>
